ğŸ’¡ 1. Origin and Evolution of Java

Java was developed by James Gosling and his team at Sun Microsystems in 1991 as part of a project called Green Project.
It was initially designed for embedded systems and consumer electronic devices like TVs and set-top boxes.

The language was originally named Oak (after an oak tree outside Goslingâ€™s office).

Later it was renamed to Java, inspired by Java coffee, due to trademark issues.

The first official version, Java 1.0, was released in 1995.

In 2010, Oracle Corporation acquired Sun Microsystems and took over Javaâ€™s development.

ğŸŒ 2. Importance of Java to the Internet

Java became the language of the Internet because of its security, portability, and platform independence.
Hereâ€™s why it was revolutionary for web technology:

Feature	Description
Platform Independence	Java programs (applets) could run on any machine through web browsers using the Java Virtual Machine (JVM).
Security	Javaâ€™s runtime environment restricts untrusted code from accessing local system resources (Sandbox model).
Dynamic & Interactive	Java applets allowed dynamic, interactive content on web pages â€” unlike static HTML pages.
Network-Centric	Java provides extensive networking libraries, making it easy to build distributed, client-server applications.

